title: Why NSW Liberals really booed Malcolm Turnbull
text:
Malcolm Turnbull shakes the hand of NSW Premier Mike Baird after his address to the NSW Liberal Party State Council in Sydney. Dallas Kilponen by Joe Aston Will Glasgow The Liberal Party's NSW council, held in Sydney over the weekend, will be remembered as the first in memory to heckle a Prime Minister. On first glance, the story seemed clear – Malcolm Turnbull erred badly by claiming in his speech to the faithful that their party is "not run by factions… or by deals in back rooms" only four weeks after both factions and their deals ultimately allowed him to topple Tony Abbott in a party room ballot.
And while it was an inexplicable lapse in political judgment and self-awareness by Team Turnbull, it's not really why the new PM copped humiliating friendly fire before the rolling cameras.
Minutes earlier, the heavily factionalised NSW division had finally passed a consensus package on internal democratic reforms of party governance, shepherded through by acting president Trent Zimmerman and supported by long-time agitator and Abbott's federal electorate chair Walter Villatora .
Villatora's original proposals, favoured strongly by the party's Right, were withdrawn on Friday and its key proponents fell in behind the compromise deal. Their passage after more than two years of fraught debate is being seen by both the moderates and the centre right as a major victory for (and credit to) Zimmerman, the leading contender to become the party's permanent president and then Joe Hockey 's successor in the federal seat of North Sydney.
Malcolm Turnbull addressing the Liberal Party's NSW state council on Saturday. Party treasurer Peter McGauran (left) and acting party president Trent Zimmerman (right) are also pictured. Dallas Kilponen But plenty of Right-wing delegates were still reeling at the pragmatic solution foisted on them by their factional bosses, and thus Turnbull got the free feedback.
Villatora's supporters, in particular, were stunned by his last-minute surrender. And it was to defend him that Abbott himself took the podium to declare the package imperfect, but a clear improvement. He could've released statement to that effect, and stayed at home, away from the cameras, but then that would be honouring his unsolicited pledge not to wreck, snipe or undermine…
